@@ -98,7 +98,7 @@ public class TarUtils {
             if (buffer[i] == 0) {
                 break;
             }
-            result.append((char) buffer[i]);
+            result.append((char) (buffer[i] & 0xFF));
         }

         return result.toString();
```

## Summary

The bug was in the `parseName` method in the `TarUtils.java` file. The issue was that when parsing names from a byte buffer, the code was directly casting bytes to chars using `(char) buffer[i]`. In Java, bytes are signed (-128 to 127), so when a byte had a value > 127, it would become negative. When this negative value was cast to a char, incorrect character values were produced due to sign extension.

The fix changes the line to `(char) (buffer[i] & 0xFF)`, which treats the byte as an unsigned value by masking off the upper bits, ensuring the correct character value is reconstructed from the byte.

This resolves the round-trip name conversion issue in the failing test `org.apache.commons.compress.archivers.tar.TarUtilsTest::testRoundTripNames`, especially when dealing with strings containing non-ASCII characters.

